2. Effect of # of preconditions in an operator template on performance

Consider the case of 3 hanoi (3 rings, 3 pegs, no other objects of concern)

Case 1

   (moveM x y)
   MOVEM from  peg-x  to peg-y
       preconds:   ISPEG peg-x  ISPEG peg-y
 
                   ONM peg-x
 
                   NOT ONS peg-x   
                   NOT ONS peg-y

Case 2

   (moveM x y z)                   
   MOVEM from  peg-x  to peg-y with s on peg-y
       preconds:   ISPEG peg-x  ISPEG peg-y
 
                   ONM peg-x
 
                   ONS peg-z

So we (could) take advantage of the fact that we are only concerned with
3 pegs in this DOMAIN.  In order for us to Move M from peg x to peg y, we 
must know that 

1. M is on peg x
2. Nothing is on top of M (only a Smaller ring could be, in this case S)
   Effectively this (clear m) precondtion could be expressed
   as knowing where S is.  If we know S is not on M than M must be clear.
   so NOT ONS peg-x expresses this fine.
3. Nothing (smaller than M) can be on the destination peg (namely S again
   in this case) - so we know that if S is not on peg-y we can apply the 
   moveM operator.  NOT ONS peg-y

OR 
   we can take advantage of the domain dependent fact that if
   NOT ONS peg-y holds and NOT ONS peg-x holds then it MUST be the
   case that ONS peg-z holds where z =/= x and z=/= y.

The effect of this is to reduce the number of preconditions a particular 
operator has (& intuitively reduce the number of preconditions that must
later be solved as goals)

BUT:

  The result of such an action is to make the OPERATOR MOVEM "easier" to
apply in that it has fewer preconditions that need to be satisfied in 
order to apply it in a given situation.

That is, the set of plans that exists in a search space in which the
operator can be applied GROWS and thus increaes the branching factor of the
search space?

Which is true?

Well - 3 hanoi tests with the simplified preconditions behaved WORSE than
the complex precondition ones.  (see tweak-results)
